WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:12.390
Good day, I'm Norman Wildberger. In today's video,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:12.390 --> 00:00:17.130
we're moving towards understanding the&nbsp;
Hindu-Arabic framework for numbers, but&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:17.130 --> 00:00:23.640
I'd like to do that by bringing together earlier&nbsp;
work that we did on poly numbers—our versions of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:23.640 --> 00:00:31.020
polynomials—and connecting that with what we've&nbsp;
been discussing about vexels relatively recently.

00:00:32.130 --> 00:00:37.680
We started talking about poly numbers, which are&nbsp;
just another name for polynomials essentially,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:37.680 --> 00:00:43.800
in the video of Math Foundations 57 and the ones&nbsp;
following that. The basic idea is very simple:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.800 --> 00:00:47.340
we have our various number systems,&nbsp;
which are a little bit different from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:47.340 --> 00:00:51.000
what we're calling things now. In&nbsp;
particular, the natural numbers 0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:55.740
1, 2, 3, we used to call num plus, and&nbsp;
now we're just referring to that as nat.

00:00:55.740 --> 00:01:01.980
So here is the main definition: a positive&nbsp;
poly number is a list of positive numbers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:01.980 --> 00:01:07.380
in other words, of natural numbers,&nbsp;
written vertically with a bracket on top,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:07.380 --> 00:01:13.560
just like this. All right, so it's a list&nbsp;
of natural numbers with a bracket on top,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:13.560 --> 00:01:20.880
and that is a positive poly number. These&nbsp;
entries are all natural numbers. There was a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:20.880 --> 00:01:27.630
little bit of ambiguity or flexibility in the way&nbsp;
we specify a poly number in the sense that we can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:27.630 --> 00:01:34.050
add additional zeros at the end, and we agree&nbsp;
that this does not change the poly number. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:34.050 --> 00:01:40.950
for example, the poly number (3, 1, 4) is the&nbsp;
same as the poly number (3, 1, 4, 0). All right,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:40.950 --> 00:01:45.660
so having defined those things, we can then do&nbsp;
some arithmetic with them, and addition is very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:45.660 --> 00:01:51.870
straightforward. Basically, the addition is just&nbsp;
a component-wise addition where, if necessary,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:51.870 --> 00:02:00.960
you add enough zeros to the shorter one so&nbsp;
that we have numbers to add all the way down.

00:02:00.960 --> 00:02:12.660
A lot more subtle was the notion of&nbsp;
multiplication of polynomials, given&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:12.660 --> 00:02:19.230
by this relatively complicated formula. So if P&nbsp;
is, say, a poly number consisting of entries Pᵢ,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:19.230 --> 00:02:25.980
and Q is the poly number consisting of entries&nbsp;
Qᵢ, and we're indexing from zero—so P₀ on top,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:25.980 --> 00:02:33.960
then P₁, then P₂, and so on—then their product&nbsp;
P times Q is that poly number R given by R₀,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:33.960 --> 00:02:42.150
R₁, R₂, and so on, where the Rₙs are given by&nbsp;
the following formula: Rₙ is obtained by taking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:42.150 --> 00:02:51.930
the sum over all k and l, natural numbers that&nbsp;
add up to n, and the thing that we're actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.930 --> 00:02:58.800
summing is the product of Pₖ with Qₗ. So we&nbsp;
take all possible products of things in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:58.800 --> 00:03:05.220
list so that the two indices sum up to the&nbsp;
index that we're interested in over here.

00:03:05.220 --> 00:03:12.750
So, for example, if we want to multiply&nbsp;
(2, 3) by (1, 5, 4), then we get this:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:12.750 --> 00:03:19.350
(2, 13, 23, 12). The way we get that is 2 times 1&nbsp;
is 2—that's the zero level. Then at the one level,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:19.350 --> 00:03:29.760
we get that by multiplying a zero with a one or a&nbsp;
one with a zero, so 2 plus 11 is 13. At level 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:29.760 --> 00:03:35.490
we get that by maybe choosing a zero and a&nbsp;
two, taking that product, or a one and a one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:35.490 --> 00:03:42.240
that product, or a two and a one at that&nbsp;
product—that last one would be 0—so we'd&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:42.240 --> 00:03:49.800
get 8 plus 15 is 23. And the third one would be&nbsp;
taking the one position here and the two position&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:56.490
and multiplying them to give us 12. Okay, so&nbsp;
this is a non-obvious kind of multiplication,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:56.490 --> 00:04:01.620
but of course, once we recognize that these&nbsp;
are just ordinary polynomials in disguise,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:01.620 --> 00:04:06.360
then this is just the usual product of&nbsp;
polynomials rewritten in this language.

00:04:06.360 --> 00:04:15.270
And then we saw that this particular poly number&nbsp;
(0, 1) plays a kind of special role—we gave it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:15.270 --> 00:04:22.590
the name alpha—and that allowed us then to write&nbsp;
a general poly number, say something like (1, 3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:22.590 --> 00:04:30.400
2), in terms of powers of alpha, so as 1 plus 3&nbsp;
alpha plus alpha squared, where the one represents&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:30.400 --> 00:04:36.310
alpha to the zero, so representing that top&nbsp;
thing there. So this is the alpha, and this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:36.310 --> 00:04:43.720
is the alpha squared, and alpha cubed and so on&nbsp;
would be just further on down here. So here's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:43.720 --> 00:04:50.860
how we then recover the usual polynomial aspect of&nbsp;
things: our poly number on this side doesn't have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:50.860 --> 00:04:57.250
any variables in it. Over here, we recognize&nbsp;
that's a familiar kind of polynomial object,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:57.250 --> 00:05:05.020
but it has this variable alpha in it. And what we&nbsp;
want to do is we want to avoid having to say what&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:05.020 --> 00:05:10.660
precisely our variable is—that's a little bit&nbsp;
of a tricky thing in mathematics. What is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:10.660 --> 00:05:15.190
variable x? What's the difference between the&nbsp;
variable x and the variable y or the variable&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:15.190 --> 00:05:22.810
t? So defining precisely what a variable is,&nbsp;
is problematic, and we can get around that by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:22.810 --> 00:05:29.260
just playing this game of really recognizing that&nbsp;
it's the coefficients that are the crucial thing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:29.260 --> 00:05:35.170
in specifying the poly number or the polynomial,&nbsp;
and then we can actually recover the variable—or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:35.170 --> 00:05:41.890
at least one variable—by this particular&nbsp;
choice of sort of a standard poly number.

00:05:41.890 --> 00:05:47.860
Now, the other main ingredient that I want to&nbsp;
bring into the story here are these vexels that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:47.860 --> 00:05:56.950
we were talking about in the context of maxels and&nbsp;
linear algebra and matrices. So a vexel was a kind&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:56.950 --> 00:06:04.900
of generalization of a vector—a somewhat larger&nbsp;
concept, a somewhat more open-ended concept—and it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:04.900 --> 00:06:10.840
arose from a prior understanding of a term called&nbsp;
a singleton. So the definition of a singleton is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:10.840 --> 00:06:19.060
that it's a one-list from natural numbers—this&nbsp;
was laid out, say, in Math Foundations 171—and I&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:19.060 --> 00:06:25.240
remind you that for us now, nat when we say&nbsp;
natural numbers, does include zero. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:25.240 --> 00:06:31.210
so we are actually extending what we did last time&nbsp;
a little bit in that, well, we're now considering&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:31.210 --> 00:06:38.380
natural numbers as being slightly bigger than it&nbsp;
was before. So that's what a singleton is—it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:38.380 --> 00:06:43.720
just basically a one-list, that is, with one&nbsp;
element, and that element has to be a natural&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:43.720 --> 00:06:49.930
number, zero, one, two, three, something like&nbsp;
that. And then a vexel is defined to be an M-set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:49.930 --> 00:06:57.520
of singletons—so an unordered collection&nbsp;
of singletons where repetition is allowed.

00:06:57.520 --> 00:07:03.430
For example, this thing here—that is a vexel.&nbsp;
There's a singleton, there's another one, there's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:03.430 --> 00:07:09.460
another one, there's another one, there's another&nbsp;
one, there's a few repeats there—the order doesn't&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:09.460 --> 00:07:16.600
matter, you can see that by the fact there's no&nbsp;
commas. So that's a multiset of singletons—that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:16.600 --> 00:07:24.130
is a vexel. And then we also talked about rather&nbsp;
particular vexels, sort of like basis vexels,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:24.130 --> 00:07:34.180
if you like, where now we're going to call them&nbsp;
e₀, e₁, e₂. Before, we just considered e₁, e₂,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:34.180 --> 00:07:38.980
and so on, but we're including zero now, so we&nbsp;
have to enlarge our story a little bit. So e₀&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:39.490 --> 00:07:47.350
is the particular vexel with just one singleton&nbsp;
in it, namely the singleton which is the list&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:47.350 --> 00:07:55.150
containing zero. e₁ is the one vexel that has the&nbsp;
singleton consisting of the list containing one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:55.150 --> 00:08:08.380
and e₂ is the vexel whose single singleton is&nbsp;
the list containing two, and so on. Okay, so yes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:08.380 --> 00:08:19.420
that's singletons and vexels—a very nice kind&nbsp;
of data structure orientation towards vectors.

00:08:19.420 --> 00:08:27.400
So now to connect these vexels, which are&nbsp;
multisets, with the more standard idea of a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:27.400 --> 00:08:35.080
vector as essentially a list, we played the&nbsp;
following game: we had a look at a vexel,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:35.080 --> 00:08:40.750
like say this one here, and we observed that the&nbsp;
objects here are in some sense naturally ordered&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:40.750 --> 00:08:45.370
because the objects are essentially one-list&nbsp;
from natural numbers, and natural numbers are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:45.370 --> 00:08:50.740
naturally ordered—there's zero, and then there's&nbsp;
one, and then there's two, and so on. So what we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:50.740 --> 00:09:00.900
can do is we can specify this M-set by creating&nbsp;
a multiplicity list for it. We've seen in other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:00.900 --> 00:09:07.200
situations that it's a useful kind of thing to&nbsp;
do—to have an M-set and then to represent it,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:07.200 --> 00:09:14.250
give an alternate way of thinking about it, as&nbsp;
a list that records how many of various things&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:14.250 --> 00:09:23.730
appear. So this thing here we could represent by&nbsp;
this, well, kind of like a list or actually a row&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:23.730 --> 00:09:31.800
freeze kind of diagram: (2, 0, 3, 2), the two&nbsp;
representing how many singleton zeros we have,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:31.800 --> 00:09:38.340
the zero here representing how many singleton ones&nbsp;
we have, how many singleton twos we have—there are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:38.340 --> 00:09:48.000
three of them right there—and how many singleton&nbsp;
threes we have—there are those two there. Or we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:55.770
could represent the same thing by a column kind&nbsp;
of vector, by a column freeze display: (2, 0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:55.770 --> 00:10:00.780
3, 2). So it's a matter of convention whether&nbsp;
we would prefer to represent this thing with a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:00.780 --> 00:10:08.160
row object or a column object. And we also&nbsp;
note that the zeros at the end are kind of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:08.160 --> 00:10:13.080
optional—we could also think about representing&nbsp;
this by including a zero here representing that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:13.080 --> 00:10:19.080
there's zero for singletons, maybe another zero&nbsp;
representing zero for singletons, and so on.

00:10:19.080 --> 00:10:28.650
So you can see now there's an obvious connection&nbsp;
between this and the poly number story, right? A&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:28.650 --> 00:10:35.700
poly number was essentially just exactly&nbsp;
like this, right? So there must be some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:35.700 --> 00:10:41.280
connection—there's obviously a connection between&nbsp;
poly numbers and vexels, and that's interesting,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:41.280 --> 00:10:48.630
I think, for us. And we just point out&nbsp;
that vexels, because they're multisets,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:48.630 --> 00:10:53.100
they can be added, because we can add any&nbsp;
two multisets, so we just loop them all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:53.100 --> 00:10:59.820
together. So if V and W are vexels, then&nbsp;
we can form V + W. We can multiply V by 2,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:59.820 --> 00:11:05.790
we can take a linear combination like&nbsp;
3V + 4W—these are all easily defined&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:06.750 --> 00:11:16.980
because V and W are vexels—they're multisets.&nbsp;
So we gain a lot of infrastructure for free by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:16.980 --> 00:11:23.880
having our objects be multisets. This is&nbsp;
a kind of theme that's underlying a lot&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:23.880 --> 00:11:29.490
of what I've been doing and will be doing&nbsp;
in the next, in the last few dozen videos.

00:11:29.490 --> 00:11:36.450
So now we want to move towards bringing in the&nbsp;
third kind of objects that we're interested in,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:36.450 --> 00:11:40.230
which are Hindu-Arabic numbers,&nbsp;
and we want to kind of bring all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:40.230 --> 00:11:45.810
of these three things together into&nbsp;
the same pie—poly numbers, vexels,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:45.810 --> 00:11:53.640
and Hindu-Arabic numbers. So it turns out&nbsp;
that essentially the same objects are good&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:53.640 --> 00:11:59.280
for describing any three of those things—a&nbsp;
natural synergy between these three things.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:59.280 --> 00:12:07.080
So to move in that direction, we need to talk&nbsp;
about how we're going to multiply vexels,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:07.080 --> 00:12:12.360
and we're going to start doing that by&nbsp;
explaining how to multiply singletons,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:12.360 --> 00:12:19.860
because vexels are M-sets of singletons. If we&nbsp;
know how to multiply singletons, hey, we know&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:19.860 --> 00:12:25.710
how to multiply M-sets of them automatically—in&nbsp;
other words, we know how to multiply vexels.

00:12:25.710 --> 00:12:31.830
So the definition of the multiplication of&nbsp;
singletons is rather surprising, perhaps,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:31.830 --> 00:12:39.030
at least if you don't know where we're heading&nbsp;
towards. Okay, so we have two singletons here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:39.030 --> 00:12:45.960
the singleton n, the singleton m, and n and&nbsp;
m are necessarily natural numbers—zero, one,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:45.960 --> 00:12:50.430
two, three, four, etc.—two of those&nbsp;
things. And we're going to define&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:50.430 --> 00:12:57.630
the product of the singleton n times the&nbsp;
singleton m to be the singleton n plus m,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:57.630 --> 00:13:10.560
where this is just the usual addition of natural&nbsp;
numbers. This is a surprising definition—we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:10.560 --> 00:13:17.880
defining a multiplication in terms of an&nbsp;
underlying addition. Actually, it reminds us&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:17.880 --> 00:13:22.830
perhaps a little bit about the tropical—doesn't&nbsp;
it? That kind of thing was going on there too.

00:13:22.830 --> 00:13:29.940
All right, so notice that singleton multiplication&nbsp;
is automatically commutative and associative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:29.940 --> 00:13:39.510
because the addition in natural numbers is. And&nbsp;
now we simply extend this multiplication to a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:39.510 --> 00:13:44.430
multiplication of vexels, because vexels&nbsp;
are M-sets of singletons, so if we know&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:44.430 --> 00:13:51.270
how to multiply singletons, then we know how to&nbsp;
multiply vexels automatically. So let me remind&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:51.270 --> 00:13:57.570
you about the general philosophy of multiplying&nbsp;
M-sets: if here is some diagram for an M-set,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:57.570 --> 00:14:02.310
and here's another M-set, and we happen to&nbsp;
know how to multiply the objects in here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:02.310 --> 00:14:07.200
by the objects in there, then here's how&nbsp;
diagrammatically we multiply the M-sets:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:07.200 --> 00:14:15.390
we just take all possible products between objects&nbsp;
in here and objects in here. So we form a new&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:15.390 --> 00:14:24.330
M-set which consists of, in this case, A times&nbsp;
D, A times E, B times D, B times E, C times D,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:24.330 --> 00:14:31.410
C times E. So in this case, it was going to&nbsp;
be three times two, six objects in this M-set.

00:14:31.410 --> 00:14:38.670
So that's a general principle that we do, no&nbsp;
matter what, in terms of multiplying M-sets.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:38.670 --> 00:14:44.670
So multiplying vexels is now straightforward.&nbsp;
So here's a vexel V, here's another vexel W,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:44.670 --> 00:14:51.360
we need to multiply them. The product is going to&nbsp;
be defined in terms of the underlying products of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:51.360 --> 00:14:59.250
the singletons contained in there, and we know&nbsp;
that that product is determined essentially&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:59.250 --> 00:15:07.740
by the addition of the numbers inside the&nbsp;
singletons. So when we multiply this singleton by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:07.740 --> 00:15:14.940
this singleton—zero times one—the singleton zero&nbsp;
times the singleton one, we get the singleton one&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:14.940 --> 00:15:21.960
because zero plus one is one. And similarly, this&nbsp;
times this one is this, this times this is this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:21.960 --> 00:15:28.500
and then this times this is that, this times this&nbsp;
is that, this times this is that, and this two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:28.500 --> 00:15:34.020
times that one is another three—two times three,&nbsp;
that'll be the five. And two times three is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:34.020 --> 00:15:38.880
five—whenever I want to say two times three is&nbsp;
five, I don't really mean the number two times&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:38.880 --> 00:15:44.640
the number three is the number five. I rather mean&nbsp;
the singleton two times the singleton three is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:44.640 --> 00:15:56.070
singleton five. Okay, and we can represent this&nbsp;
by thinking about the corresponding pictures,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:56.070 --> 00:16:03.150
descriptions of these vexels in terms&nbsp;
of row or column freeze type vectors.

00:16:03.150 --> 00:16:10.830
So this thing here, this vexel, is described&nbsp;
by (2, 0, 1)—there's two zeros, 0, 1, and 1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:10.830 --> 00:16:18.810
2. This one here is described by (0, 1, 0,&nbsp;
2)—there are zero zeros, a one, one, zero twos,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:18.810 --> 00:16:26.280
and two threes. And this one here is given by&nbsp;
this thing here. And then if you think about it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:26.280 --> 00:16:31.680
for a little while, you can convince yourself&nbsp;
that this product here is in fact exactly the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:31.680 --> 00:16:39.090
same as poly number multiplication—these&nbsp;
things look like poly numbers. You have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:39.090 --> 00:16:45.750
a green border here instead of a bracket up&nbsp;
on top, but otherwise, they're just the same.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:45.750 --> 00:16:54.810
And you can check that this is exactly the same&nbsp;
as corresponding poly number multiplication. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:54.810 --> 00:17:03.270
this is another way of thinking about poly number&nbsp;
multiplication—it's really generated by this very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:03.270 --> 00:17:10.170
simple multiplication of singletons—it's&nbsp;
really only that one equation involved.

00:17:10.170 --> 00:17:15.870
Okay, so we're seeing that there's a very&nbsp;
close connection between vexels and poly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:15.870 --> 00:17:24.360
numbers—they're almost the same thing. And&nbsp;
here are some of the laws for the arithmetic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:24.360 --> 00:17:29.730
with vexels that we can easily deduce from&nbsp;
our definitions. And in fact, these laws&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:29.730 --> 00:17:39.360
are almost automatic now—there's not any serious&nbsp;
difficulty in seeing why they're true. So if V,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:39.360 --> 00:17:45.600
W, and U are vexels, and say N and M happen to&nbsp;
be natural numbers, then we have commutativity&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:45.600 --> 00:17:50.520
of addition and associativity of addition,&nbsp;
because the addition of vexels is basically&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:50.520 --> 00:17:56.670
just M-set addition, and we know that's&nbsp;
commutative. We know that we can multiply,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:56.670 --> 00:18:05.040
say, a sum V + W by some natural number N, and&nbsp;
that's the same as N times V plus N times W.

00:18:05.040 --> 00:18:10.710
With regard to our multiplication, well,&nbsp;
the commutativity and the associativity of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:10.710 --> 00:18:16.410
the multiplication follows immediately from&nbsp;
the commutativity and associativity of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:16.410 --> 00:18:23.610
multiplication at the singleton level, which is a&nbsp;
consequence of the commutativity and associativity&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:23.610 --> 00:18:33.270
for natural number addition. We have some other&nbsp;
laws having to do with how numbers multiply&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:33.270 --> 00:18:37.950
vexels, which are pretty straightforward. We have&nbsp;
the important distributive laws, and these, again,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:37.950 --> 00:18:44.400
are just natural consequences of the fact that&nbsp;
we've defined our multiplication in an M-set kind&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:44.400 --> 00:18:50.880
of way, in a multiset orientation depending&nbsp;
on an interior multiplication of elements.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:50.880 --> 00:18:54.840
So whenever you have such a situation,&nbsp;
these distributive laws are automatic.

00:18:54.840 --> 00:19:00.810
And it's useful to observe that we&nbsp;
have a special vexel, the zero vexel,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:00.810 --> 00:19:08.670
which is just the empty M-set, because vexels are&nbsp;
M-sets, so there's an empty M-set, and that zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:08.670 --> 00:19:14.490
vexel satisfies that when you add it to anything,&nbsp;
you get the anything, and when you multiply zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:14.490 --> 00:19:23.940
times V in either order, you get zero. So it sort&nbsp;
of acts like zero does. So it's very pleasant that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:23.940 --> 00:19:31.680
these laws of arithmetic are almost automatic&nbsp;
here—the way we've set things up, they just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:31.680 --> 00:19:37.890
fall nicely into place, and essentially no work&nbsp;
is required to understand them, to prove them.

00:19:37.890 --> 00:19:45.990
And there's also a distinguished vexel, simple&nbsp;
but distinguished vexel—this vexel (0, 1),&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:45.990 --> 00:19:54.870
which officially is the M-set consisting of just&nbsp;
the singleton with one in it. And previously we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:54.870 --> 00:20:01.090
called that α₁, but now we see that it plays&nbsp;
exactly the same role as alpha in the context&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:01.090 --> 00:20:07.690
of poly numbers. So in other words, we can now&nbsp;
introduce alpha in this vexel context by saying,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:07.690 --> 00:20:14.110
let's agree that this particular thing is alpha.&nbsp;
In other words, we're defining e₁ to be alpha.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:14.110 --> 00:20:24.250
Well, then if you square it, you square this&nbsp;
thing here—you have to add one plus one, you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:24.250 --> 00:20:32.260
get the vexel which has a single singleton with&nbsp;
a two, alpha cubed will be the singleton three,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:32.260 --> 00:20:42.160
and so on. And so now we can write any vexel V in&nbsp;
terms of essentially two equivalent forms—in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:42.160 --> 00:20:53.440
form as a linear combination of e₀, e₁, e₂, up to&nbsp;
eₖ, as well as e₀, or correspondingly in terms of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:53.440 --> 00:21:03.700
powers of alpha, alpha to the zero, alpha to the&nbsp;
one, alpha to the two, and so on, out to say aₖ&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:04.420 --> 00:21:13.120
times alpha to the k, where we also introduced&nbsp;
alpha to the zero to mean this e₀ vexel here.

00:21:13.120 --> 00:21:20.230
So we have a kind of linear algebra point&nbsp;
of view on vexels represented by this,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:20.230 --> 00:21:26.440
or we have a poly number or polynomial point&nbsp;
of view towards vexels represented by this.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:26.440 --> 00:21:33.220
And this is very nice to have these&nbsp;
two different aspects of things sitting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:33.220 --> 00:21:40.330
inside the same structure—that means we can do&nbsp;
polynomial kinds of manipulations or thinking,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:40.330 --> 00:21:48.730
and we can do linear algebra kinds of thinking&nbsp;
in the same context, so that linear algebra&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:48.730 --> 00:21:54.070
and the calculus kind of can interact more&nbsp;
freely and pleasantly in this kind of setup.

00:21:54.070 --> 00:21:59.800
So by introducing this multiplication of&nbsp;
vexels, we are getting this convergence&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:59.800 --> 00:22:07.150
of fundamental mathematical objects—vectors&nbsp;
and polynomials—they become essentially the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:07.150 --> 00:22:15.100
same kinds of things. So this is a traditional&nbsp;
vector, (3, 1, 2, 0, -5), and now we know that,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:15.100 --> 00:22:20.650
well, we should really think about that probably&nbsp;
in terms of a vexel rather than as a vector. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:20.650 --> 00:22:27.700
when we do that, then we naturally can&nbsp;
associate it to the vexel written as 3&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:27.700 --> 00:22:35.170
plus alpha plus 2 alpha squared plus 5 alpha&nbsp;
to the four. So vector, polynomial—some kind&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:35.170 --> 00:22:42.820
of connection there. And we realize that both&nbsp;
of these objects are just manifestations of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:42.820 --> 00:22:50.830
underlying object, which is neither a list nor&nbsp;
a polynomial, but rather this underlying M-set.

00:22:50.830 --> 00:22:58.690
Okay, so the underlying M-set has three zeros, a&nbsp;
single one, a couple of twos, no threes, and five&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:58.690 --> 00:23:07.510
fours, and it's really at this multiset level that&nbsp;
the operations become simplest to define and the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:07.510 --> 00:23:14.590
laws are easiest to verify. So mathematically,&nbsp;
this is where things want to live. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:14.590 --> 00:23:23.440
the interpretations of this object as a vector,&nbsp;
or as a polynomial, or as a poly number, or as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:23.440 --> 00:23:29.710
something else—maybe a column vector rather than a&nbsp;
row vector, for example—these are interpretations&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:29.710 --> 00:23:36.160
that we bring to this underlying object,&nbsp;
which is just a data structure, a multiset.

00:23:36.160 --> 00:23:45.310
In our next video, we want to now connect&nbsp;
more closely with the Hindu-Arabic story.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:45.310 --> 00:23:49.570
How do Hindu-Arabic numbers&nbsp;
and the usual arithmetic that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:49.570 --> 00:23:55.840
we're very familiar with slot into this&nbsp;
situation? We'll explain that next time.

00:23:55.840 --> 00:24:00.760
I hope you'll join me for that. I'm&nbsp;
Norman Wildberger, thanks for listening.

